{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588421"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:07:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:07:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15136"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15136"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.44,0.13,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69311"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7824"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15136"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54764"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"},{"type":"tags","id":"5528"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"10521"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19086"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69311"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUrinary tract infections (UTIs) show significant variation in prevalence across different geographical regions and populations worldwide.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains regional and population-based variation in urinary tract infection rates?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anatomical differences between populations","Seasonal temperature variations","Genetic resistance to antibiotics","Soil bacterial content","Dietary protein intake"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnatomical differences between populations\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. The most significant factor in UTI prevalence is anatomical variation, particularly the shorter urethral length in women compared to men, which accounts for higher rates in females.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eseasonal temperature variations\u003C/strong\u003E may have minor effects on bacterial growth, this is not a major determinant of population differences. \u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic resistance to antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E affects treatment success but not initial infection rates. \u003Cstrong\u003ESoil bacterial content\u003C/strong\u003E has minimal impact on UTI prevalence as urinary pathogens are typically from the body\u0027s own flora. \u003Cstrong\u003EDietary protein intake\u003C/strong\u003E does not significantly influence UTI rates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important factors include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccess to healthcare and sanitation facilities\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAge distribution of the population\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECultural practices around hygiene\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevalence of underlying medical conditions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urinary tract infection rates vary by anatomical differences between sexes, with women having higher rates due to shorter urethral length","Socioeconomic factors influence UTI rates through access to hygiene facilities and healthcare","Age-related factors affect UTI risk, with higher rates in elderly populations and young children","Cultural practices around toileting and intimate hygiene impact UTI prevalence"],"references":["Tandogdu Z, Wagenlehner FM. Global epidemiology of urinary tract infections. Curr Opin Infect Dis. 2016 Feb;29(1):73-9. doi: 10.1097/QCO.0000000000000228. PMID: 26694621.","Foxman B. The epidemiology of urinary tract infection. Nat Rev Urol. 2010 Dec;7(12):653-60. doi: 10.1038/nrurol.2010.190. PMID: 21139641.","Medina M, Castillo-Pino E. An introduction to the epidemiology and burden of urinary tract infections. Ther Adv Urol. 2019 May 2;11:1756287219832172. doi: 10.1177/1756287219832172. PMID: 31105774; PMCID: PMC6502976."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54764"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15136"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54764"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:13:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:19:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7824"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69311"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"